passages.text: FY25 NPAT a miss but a return price catalysts should see stock well supported, retain Overweight

Key takeaways: 1) The FY25 EBITDA loss of \(\cdot 517\mathrm{m}\) was in- line with JPMc, while elevated non- cash expenses saw the earnings loss of \(\cdot 534\mathrm{m}\) greater than JPMc/BBG cons of \(\cdot 511 / - 514\mathrm{m}\) . On a more positive note, Honeymoon generated \(\mathbb{S}17.4\mathrm{m}\) of free cashflow for the year; 2) BOE's balance sheet remains in good shape, with a net cash balance of \(\mathbb{S}37\mathrm{m}\) and a further \(\mathbb{S}52\mathrm{m}\) in investments/liquid assets and \(\mathbb{S}120\mathrm{m}\) in inventories; 3) No changes were made to production and cost guidance from the JunQ result, with the independent review still pending. Following the result, our NPV is down \(4\%\) to \(\mathbb{S}2.14\mathrm{ps}\) after adjusting corporate costs higher and our FY26 NPAT is down \(7\%\) to \(\mathbb{S}77\mathrm{m}\) after lowering Alta Mesa production slightly. With BOE screening with \(10\%\) potential upside to our \(\mathbb{S}2.15\mathrm{ps}\) PT and uranium prices well supported as the market emerges from its seasonal lull, we retain our Overweight rating.

EBITDA in- line but NPAT a miss. BOE reported an FY25 EBITDA loss of \(\cdot 517\mathrm{m}\) , which was in- line with JPMc, but below BBG consensus of \(\cdot 511\mathrm{m}\) . However, non- cash expenses associated with cost of sales along with higher D&A led to an earnings loss of \(\mathbb{S}34\mathrm{m}\) , coming in well below JPMc and consensus of \(\cdot 511\mathrm{m}\) and \(\cdot 514\mathrm{m}\) , respectively. Honeymoon reported positive free cashflow of \(\mathbb{S}17.4\mathrm{m}\) for the year. The company's balance sheet remains in good condition, with a cash balance of \(\mathbb{S}37\mathrm{m}\) (pre- reported), \(\mathbb{S}52\mathrm{m}\) in investments and liquid assets and \(\mathbb{S}120\mathrm{m}\) of inventory on hand. No changes were made to the FY26 production guidance of \(1.6\mathrm{Ml}\) b U3O8 at an all- in sustaining cost (AISC) of \(\mathrm{A}\mathbb{S}64 - 70 / \mathrm{lb}\) and total capex of \(\mathbb{S}56 - 62\mathrm{m}\) . No updates were provided on the independent review at Honeymoon which is still ongoing.

Uranium prices to be well supported following a round of production cuts. Over the past week, uranium equities have rallied (BOE \(+11\%\) , PDN \(+13\%\) vs ASX200 \(+0.3\%\) ) and the spot uranium price is up \(\mathbb{S}3 / \mathrm{lb}\) to \(\mathbb{S}75 / \mathrm{lb}\) following news that Kazatomprom is cutting its 2026 production guidance by \(10\%\) to \(77.2\mathrm{Ml}\) b (from \(85.2\mathrm{Ml}\) b), with Cameco also downgrading 2025 production at McArthur River/ Key Lake to \(14 - 15\mathrm{Ml}\) b (from \(18\mathrm{Ml}\) b), placing further pressure on what is already a tight market. Furthermore, we expect term contracting activity to pick up again heading into September on usual seasonality and following the World Nuclear Association Symposium in London, acting as an additional tailwind for uranium prices.

Retain Overweight. Following the result, our NPV is down \(4\%\) to \(\mathbb{S}2.14\mathrm{ps}\) as we adjust our corporate costs higher. After reducing FY26 ALta Mesa production lower to \(970\mathrm{k}\mathrm{l}\mathrm{b}\) U3O8 \((100\%\) basis) our FY26 NPAT falls \(7\%\) to \(\mathbb{S}77\mathrm{m}\) . While we acknowledge the review at Honeymoon on the continuity of mineralization and leachability remains an overhang, we believe our estimates already account for this uncertainty. With BOE offering \(10\%\) potential upside to our \(\mathbb{S}2.15\mathrm{ps}\) PT and our expectation that uranium prices will be well supported over the course of the year, we retain our Overweight rating.

Boss Energy (BOE AU) is an Australian- based pure- play uranium miner. The company's flagship key asset is its \(100\%\) - owned Honeymoon Uranium Project in South Australia, which returned to commercial production in January 2025 after being placed on care and maintenance in 2013 due to technical issues and low uranium prices. BOE also holds a \(30\%\) non- operational stake in the Alta Mesa uranium project in South Texas (enCore Energy \(70\%\) ), which also returned to commercial production in June 2024 after being placed on care and maintenance in 2013 due to low uranium prices. We rate BOE Overweight based on valuation.
Our Jun- 26 price target is based on our NPV valuation using a discount rate of \(8.1\%\) .
